# React Enterprise Checklist (100 Rules Audit)

Use this checklist for:
- code review across teams
- pre go-live architecture audit
- large refactor validation
- onboarding quality baseline

## Stack Assumptions
- TanStack Query
- Zustand
- React Hook Form
- Zod
- Next.js + React

## 1) Architecture (15 rules)
- Feature-based architecture is enforced.
- Project is not organized only by technical layers.
- `features/` folder exists and is actively used.
- `hooks/`, `services/api`, `types/`, and `schemas/` are clearly present.
- UI components are separated from business logic.
- API layer is separated from view components.
- No circular dependencies across feature modules.
- Feature modules are independently maintainable.
- Component files are kept below 300 lines.
- Reusable primitives live in `components/ui`.
- No duplicated component implementations.
- Design system conventions are documented and used.
- Module ownership boundaries are clear.
- Import paths and alias strategy are consistent.
- Architecture decisions support long-term scaling.

## 2) Data Fetching (10 rules)
- No direct API calls in UI components.
- TanStack Query is used for server state.
- Every query has a stable `queryKey`.
- Retry behavior is explicit where appropriate.
- Caching is configured intentionally.
- Loading state is always handled.
- Error state is always handled.
- Empty state is always handled.
- Duplicate fetches for same endpoint are avoided.
- API logic is centralized in services/feature api modules.

## 3) State Management (10 rules)
- Server state is not stored in global store.
- Zustand is used for global UI/app state only.
- No duplicated state sources.
- Prop drilling deeper than 3 levels is avoided.
- Global stores remain small and domain-scoped.
- Store state and actions are strongly typed.
- Context usage is limited and intentional.
- Stores are split by domain responsibility.
- No hidden side effects inside stores.
- State update flow is predictable and testable.

## 4) Rendering and Performance (15 rules)
- Massive tables/lists are not rendered unvirtualized.
- Virtualization is used for very large datasets.
- TanStack columns/data are memoized where needed.
- `React.memo` is used for expensive render trees when beneficial.
- `useMemo` is used for heavy calculations.
- `useCallback` is used for unstable handlers in hot paths.
- Inline callbacks in large list renders are minimized.
- Small state changes do not trigger full-page rerenders.
- Heavy components are lazy loaded/dynamically imported.
- Code splitting strategy is enabled.
- Bundle size budget is monitored.
- Avoid importing entire libraries unnecessarily.
- Duplicate data fetch paths are eliminated.
- Layout rerender churn is controlled.
- Suspense/loading skeleton strategy is consistent.

## 5) Component Design (10 rules)
- Components are reusable by design.
- Heavy business logic is extracted from UI files.
- Props are fully typed and explicit.
- Components are pure when possible.
- No hardcoded product text in reusable components.
- No hardcoded style values that break design system.
- UI building blocks are independent and composable.
- Layout components are separated from feature widgets.
- Modal primitives are reusable.
- Table primitives are reusable.

## 6) Forms (10 rules)
- React Hook Form is used for complex forms.
- Zod schemas drive validation.
- Schemas are separated into dedicated files.
- No per-input `useState` anti-pattern for large forms.
- Error messages are clear and actionable.
- Submit is disabled during pending requests.
- Form reset behavior is explicit and correct.
- Form logic duplication is avoided.
- Input components are reusable.
- Client and server validation contracts stay aligned.

## 7) Tables and Lists (10 rules)
- Reusable table component exists and is adopted.
- TanStack Table is used for enterprise data grids.
- Large dataset sorting is server-side.
- Pagination is server-side for large datasets.
- Search/filtering uses debounce.
- Columns configuration supports dynamic needs.
- Stable row keys are always used.
- Loading state exists for table views.
- Empty state exists for table views.
- Error state exists for table views.

## 8) Next.js Specific (10 rules)
- Server Components are preferred when possible.
- Client Components are used only when necessary.
- Server-side fetching is used when appropriate.
- Layouts avoid unnecessary rerenders on navigation.
- Route structure remains clear and maintainable.
- Layout logic is not duplicated.
- Static generation is used where beneficial.
- SEO metadata is configured consistently.
- API fetching is not duplicated across many components.
- Dynamic import is used for heavy feature widgets.

## 9) Code Quality (10 rules)
- TypeScript strict mode is enabled.
- `any` usage is controlled and justified.
- ESLint rules are active and enforced.
- Formatting is standardized.
- Absolute imports are used (for example `@/...`).
- Error handling is complete and explicit.
- Frontend error logging strategy is in place.
- API URLs are not hardcoded.
- Environment variables are documented and consistent.
- Error Boundary is present for resilient UI shells.

## Audit Scoring
- Pass > 85 rules: enterprise-ready.
- Pass 70-85 rules: production-acceptable with improvement plan.
- Pass < 70 rules: refactor required before scale-up.

## Critical Warning Signals
- API calls inside view components.
- Large tables rendered without pagination/virtualization.
- Manual or duplicated validation logic.
- Bloated global state and duplicated data sources.
- Oversized bundles with poor loading performance.
